      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yeah, in packages the main binary is supposed to always be called literally \"app\", renamed during packaging. The package is a self-contained thing, so that\u0027s the main entry point, and it can\u0027t generally see outside its package, and so all packages\u0027 binaries are called \"app\".\n\nHowever, when running in-tree, they\u0027re not using packages yet, hence all this hacking to find things in /system/ where the binaries live now.\n\nWhen running standalone, I\u0027m copying to /tmp and faking packages with the `namespace` command which is a command line way to create a directory view, to make it appear to the child that it\u0027s inside a package. But I wasn\u0027t sure how to do some of the self-invoking tests, so it \"fixes\" argv[0] with the --replace-child-argv0 argument to namespace (but I added that argument, so I\u0027m not sure it\u0027s going to be widely used!).\n\nBasically it\u0027s a bit of a mess right now, so hopefully it can get rationalized soon.",
